        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 34-year-old Czech male who presents to the outpatient urology clinic in Prague complaining of a 5-day history of burning discomfort during urination, increased urinary frequency, and a persistent dull aching sensation in his lower abdomen [MEDDIALOG:N39.0:0]. He appears mildly uncomfortable but is in no acute distress. His face is slightly flushed and he reports feeling fatigued and generally unwell throughout the week [MEDDIALOG:N39.0:0].\n\n{patientName} works as a software developer at a mid-sized tech company in Prague, spending the majority of his workday seated at a desk. Outside of work, he enjoys recreational cycling along the Vltava River on weekends and plays football with friends on Thursday evenings. He lives with his long-term partner in a flat in Vinohrady. His social circle is close-knit and he occasionally drinks beer at weekend gatherings, but does not smoke.\n\nHe describes the dysuria as a burning pain that worsens at the end of micturition, accompanied by an urgency to urinate more frequently than usual, including two to three times during the night [MEDDIALOG:N39.0:0]. He also notes that his urine appears slightly cloudy. He denies frank haematuria, flank pain, or fever above 38 °C, suggesting the infection has remained in the lower urinary tract. He has not noticed any discharge from the urethra."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:45f0ef23-77bf-441a-bbdd-66a97d796911",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
