            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no significant chronic medical conditions. He reports a single episode of antibiotic-treated UTI approximately 18 months ago that resolved without complications [MEDDIALOG:N39.0:2]. He completed a short course of oral antibiotics at that time but cannot recall the specific agent. He has no history of hospitalisation, urological surgery, or known structural anomalies of the urinary tract. He is not immunocompromised and takes no regular prescription medications. He has a documented allergy to amoxicillin (rash). He does not use recreational drugs. His fluid intake is moderate; he acknowledges he does not drink enough water on workdays, which may contribute to urinary stasis. There is no history of sexually transmitted infections. His father has a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, which is a known predisposing factor for recurrent UTI [MEDDIALOG:N39.0:0]. {patientName} himself has normal fasting blood glucose on routine screening."
          }
        ]
      }
